**PURPOSE & SCOPE**

This memo documents 8 specific changes to the AI takeoff system rules,
derived from comparing our AI-generated material takeoff against Burton
Lumber Quote #1336139. Each change targets a systematic gap or
methodology difference found in that comparison. The table below shows
which source document each change affects.

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Category**          **Affected Project File**
  --------------------- ---------------------------------------------------------
  RULEBOOK UPDATE       Residential_Takeoff_Rulebook_AI_Formulas.pdf

  EXTRACTION LOGIC      Standard_Residential_Construction_Manual_AI_Takeoff.pdf

  NEW EXTRACTION        Common_Assumptions_Checklist_USA_Residential.pdf
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------

> **LIABILITY NOTE: Changes #1, #4, and #5 remove automatic
> waste/overage factors from output quantities. The GC assumes
> responsibility for waste factor decisions. A standard liability clause
> is included at the end of this document.**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------
  **#1**   **REBAR --- Standardize All Output to #4 x 20-ft    **RULEBOOK
           Sticks**                                            UPDATE**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------

**Problem**

Our takeoff split rebar into 3 line items (footing bars, wall bars, wire
mesh) reported in linear feet. Burton ordered everything as #4 x 20-ft
sticks, which is the actual field purchase unit. The split caused a
perceived 140% discrepancy when total quantities were broadly comparable
--- the disconnect was purely methodological.

**Rule Change --- Rulebook Section 6.4**

Replace Section 6.4 with the following:

> REBAR OUTPUT RULE (updated):
>
> 1\. Calculate ALL rebar for all elements as a single combined linear
> footage:
>
> Footing continuous bars \[LF\]
>
> Foundation wall vertical \[LF\]
>
> Foundation wall horizontal \[LF\]
>
> J-bar dowels (30\" leg) \[LF\] -\> also list as \[N\] EA
>
> Slab/transition dowels \[LF\]
>
> Pier cage bars \[LF\]
>
> TOTAL \[LF\]
>
> 2\. Convert to #4 x 20-ft sticks:
>
> TotalSticks = ceil(TotalRebarLF / 20)
>
> 3\. Output ONE purchase line: \'#4 Rebar x 20-ft sticks \-- \[N\] EA\'
>
> Show the LF breakdown by element as a sub-table below it.
>
> 4\. Do NOT apply a waste multiplier to the stick count.
>
> Add note: \'GC to add waste/cutting allowance per their practice.\'

**Liability Clause --- Add to Rebar Output**

> **FYI / ESTIMATING LIABILITY: Rebar reported as net linear footage
> converted to #4 x 20-ft purchase sticks with NO waste factor applied.
> Cutting waste, lap splices, and field adjustments are the GC\'s
> responsibility. These quantities are an estimating baseline only and
> do not constitute a stamped structural material list.**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------
  **#2**   **WALL FRAMING --- Add Plates + Treated Bottom      **RULEBOOK
           Plate Logic**                                       UPDATE**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------

**Problem**

Our takeoff counted cavity studs only. We reported plates as a combined
LF item but did not integrate them per wall segment, and we did not flag
which bottom plates required pressure treatment. Burton\'s quote calls
out treated plates explicitly as separate line items (2x4-16 Borate
Treated .17 and 2x6-16 Borate Treated .17).

**Rule Change --- Rulebook Section 3.3**

> PLATE COUNTING RULE (updated):
>
> For each wall segment, output ALL of the following:
>
> BOTTOM PLATE:
>
> Is this wall sitting on concrete?
>
> Test: wall at basement level OR above slab/garage floor?
>
> YES -\> TREATED bottom plate (Borate .17 or PT per spec)
>
> NO -\> Standard bottom plate (same species as studs)
>
> Qty: BottomPlateLF = WallLengthLF (1 plate)
>
> TOP PLATE:
>
> Bearing wall (all exterior + interior bearing):
>
> DOUBLE top plate -\> TopPlateLF = WallLengthLF x 2
>
> Non-bearing partition:
>
> SINGLE top plate -\> TopPlateLF = WallLengthLF x 1
>
> OUTPUT FORMAT (per wall type per level):
>
> Studs: \[N\] EA 2x6 @ 92-5/8\"
>
> Bottom plate (PT): \[LF\] 2x6-16 Borate Treated .17 \<- on concrete
>
> Bottom plate (std): \[LF\] 2x6-16 Std&Btr Fir \<- on wood
>
> Top plate (dbl): \[LF\] 2x6-16 Std&Btr Fir (x2)
>
> TREATED PLATE TRIGGER:
>
> Basement exterior/interior walls -\> ALWAYS treated (sits on slab)
>
> Main floor exterior walls -\> ALWAYS treated (per A11 note)
>
> Main floor interior partitions -\> Standard (sits on T&G subfloor)
>
> Garage walls -\> ALWAYS treated (sits on garage slab)

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Wall Location**     **Bottom Plate**   **Trigger / Source**
  --------------------- ------------------ ------------------------------
  Basement exterior     2x6 PT / Borate    Sits on foundation wall ---
  walls                 Treated            SD1 detail 1/2

  Basement interior     2x4 PT / Borate    Sits on basement slab --- A2
  partitions            Treated            floor plan

  Main floor exterior   2x6 PT / Borate    A11: \'PT sole plates at all
  walls                 Treated            exterior walls\'

  Main floor interior   2x4 standard       Sits on 3/4\" T&G subfloor
  (non-bearing)                            over I-joists

  Garage walls          2x6 PT / Borate    Sits on garage slab --- A2
                        Treated            plan, SD3 notes

  Porch / deck ledger   PT as required     Exterior exposure --- SD1 deck
                                           detail 17
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------
  **#3**   **INTERIOR DOORS --- Identify and List ALL Door     **EXTRACTION
           Types**                                             LOGIC**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------

**Problem**

Our takeoff counted 31 interior doors (primary rooms only). Burton had
49 units because they included closet doors, pocket doors, bifold doors,
and utility room doors. We did not categorize door type (bifold, pocket,
barn, standard swing) which is critical for ordering the correct frame
and hardware system.

**New Extraction Rule --- Add to Rulebook Section 8 Checklist**

> DOOR EXTRACTION RULE (new):
>
> Scan EVERY room on EVERY floor plan. Do not limit to primary rooms.
>
> Include: bedrooms, bathrooms, closets (walk-in, reach-in, linen,
> coat),
>
> utility, laundry, mechanical, pantry, mud room, garage entry.
>
> FOR EACH DOOR, record:
>
> 1\. Location (room + floor level)
>
> 2\. Nominal size (e.g. \'2668\' = 2\'6\" x 6\'8\")
>
> 3\. Door TYPE per the classification below

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Plan Symbol**     **Door Type      **Hardware / Frame Implication**
                      Code**           
  ------------------- ---------------- -----------------------------------
  Arc swing, single   SW Standard      Prehung unit. Passage or privacy
  leaf                Swing            knob.

  Dashed rectangle    PD Pocket Door   Requires pocket door frame kit. No
  inside wall                          hinge hardware.
  thickness                            

  Double arc, two     DB Double /      Two-leaf prehung or two separate
  panels              French           slabs.

  Two opposing arcs   BF Bifold        Bifold hardware kit: track + pivot
  (folding)                            pins.

  Single panel        BD Barn Door     Bypass hardware + wall-mount track.
  side-hung on track                   

  Two panels          BP Bypass        Bypass hardware. Common in closets.
  side-by-side bypass Sliding          

  Arc + \'FR\' or     FR Fire Rated    20-min min at garage-to-living per
  \'20-min\' note                      IRC.

  Overhead panel      OH Overhead      Separate line item.
  (garage)                             Contractor-installed.
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

> OUTPUT FORMAT:
>
> Standard Swing (SW): 2668 HC: \[N\] EA / 2868 HC: \[N\] EA / 3068:
> \[N\] EA
>
> Pocket Door (PD): 2668: \[N\] EA -\> also \[N\] EA pocket door frame
> kits
>
> Bifold (BF): \[size\]: \[N\] EA -\> \[N\] bifold hardware kits
>
> Fire Rated (FR): \[size\] 20-min: \[N\] EA (garage separation)
>
> TOTAL INTERIOR DOORS: \[N\] EA
>
> TOTAL POCKET DOOR FRAME KITS: \[N\] EA \<- separate purchase item
>
> **SCAN TIP: Pocket door symbols are a dashed rectangle inside the wall
> thickness --- easy to miss at reduced scale. Always inspect wall
> cavities. On Burt plans: 5 pocket doors total (2 basement on A2, 3
> main floor on A3).**

