  **#4**   **ROOF SHEATHING OSB --- Exact Count, No Waste      **RULEBOOK
           Factor**                                            UPDATE**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------

**Problem**

Rulebook Section 5.4 applied a 12% sheet goods multiplier, giving us 196
sheets vs Burton\'s field-measured 152 sheets --- a 44-sheet overage
worth \~\$800. The GC determines waste allowance in the field. Our job
is an accurate net count.

**Rule Change --- Section 5.4**

> ROOF SHEATHING RULE (updated):
>
> DeckingSF = TrueRoofAreaSF (slope-corrected, NO multiplier)
>
> Sheets4x8 = ceil(DeckingSF / 32)
>
> Output: \'\[N\] sheets 4x8 \[thickness\] OSB \-- net count, no waste
> factor\'
>
> Note: \'GC to add cutting allowance. Typical field waste 5-10%
>
> depending on number of hips/valleys.\'
>
> REMOVE: DeckingSF = TrueRoofAreaSF x 1.12 \<- delete this line
>
> REPLACE WITH: DeckingSF = TrueRoofAreaSF \<- no multiplier

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------
  **#5**   **SUBFLOOR T&G OSB --- Exact Count, No Waste        **RULEBOOK
           Factor**                                            UPDATE**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- -------------

**Problem**

Same issue as Roof Sheathing. Rulebook Section 7 applied 1.12 multiplier
giving 86 sheets vs Burton\'s 72 sheets --- a +19% gap that is entirely
our waste factor, not a real quantity difference.

**Rule Change --- Section 7**

> SUBFLOOR RULE (updated):
>
> SubfloorSheets = ceil(FloorAreaSF / 32) \<- NO waste multiplier
>
> Output: \'\[N\] sheets 4x8 3/4\" T&G OSB \-- net count, no waste
> factor\'
>
> Note: \'GC to add cutting allowance. Typical field waste 8-12%
>
> for subfloor depending on floor plan complexity.\'
>
> REMOVE: SubfloorSheets = ceil((FloorAreaSF x 1.12) / 32)
>
> REPLACE WITH: SubfloorSheets = ceil(FloorAreaSF / 32)
>
> **NOTE: This change removes waste factors from Roof OSB and Subfloor
> only. Wall sheathing and drywall waste factors remain in place because
> those involve complex cuts around openings. If a client requests
> waste-included counts, note it explicitly as \'includes \[X\]% waste
> per client request.\'**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------
  **#6**   **SUSPENDED SLAB / B-DECK --- Always Report         **NEW
           Dimensions + SF**                                   EXTRACTION**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------

**Problem**

The suspended slab zone (garage level cast-in-place slab on corrugated
B-deck form) was flagged in our takeoff as \'missing --- requires
further detail.\' Burton\'s quote confirms 113 SF of 22-gauge galvanized
B-deck is real and required. The S1 and SD1 sheets had enough
information to calculate it --- we just didn\'t extract it.

**New Extraction Rule --- Add to Rulebook Section 8 Checklist**

> SUSPENDED SLAB / FORM DECK EXTRACTION RULE (new):
>
> When reading foundation plan (S1) or structural details (SD1):
>
> Look for any area labeled: SUSPENDED SLAB, CAST-IN-PLACE SLAB,
>
> SUSP. SLAB, COMP DECK, B-DECK, DECK FORM, or hatch with note.
>
> For each suspended slab zone found:
>
> a\. Extract length x width from plan dimensions
>
> b\. Compute SF = Length_LF x Width_LF
>
> c\. Note deck gauge and profile from structural notes
>
> (22 ga 1-1/2\" B-deck is standard residential per SD1)
>
> OUTPUT line item:
>
> Galvanized B-Deck Form \-- \[N\] SF
>
> Dimensions: \[L\]\' x \[W\]\' = \[SF\] SF
>
> Spec: 22 ga galvanized 1-1/2\" ribbed B-deck per SD1
>
> Min 3\" bearing on supports. Shore spans \> 6\' per SD1.
>
> Concrete for this slab is included in suspended slab CY total.
>
> If dimensions are not shown but area is visible:
>
> State \'B-deck present \-- confirm dimensions from full-size plans\'
>
> Provide bounding-box estimate from visible plan geometry.
>
> Do NOT skip or fully flag as missing if the element is visible.

**Burt Plans Reference**

On S1: The suspended slab zone is labeled \'SF24 P12\' with a hatched
area in the upper-left of the foundation plan. The cast-in-place slab
table on S1 specifies: slab = 6\"-8\" thick on 22-ga 1-1/2\" B-deck.
Dimension from plan geometry: approximately 10\' x 11\' = 110-113 SF
(Burton confirmed 113 SF).

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------
  **#7**   **MDF TRIM & CASING --- Estimate From Plan Data,    **EXTRACTION
           Not From Schedule**                                 LOGIC**

  -------- --------------------------------------------------- --------------

**Problem**

Our takeoff flagged MDF trim as \'missing --- no trim profile schedule
provided.\' Burton produced a full MDF trim schedule (\$1,515 value)
from the same plans. The information needed to estimate trim exists in
the door/window schedule plus standard casing rules. We do not need a
dedicated trim schedule to calculate it.

**New Extraction Rule --- Add to Construction Manual, Finish Section**

> MDF TRIM EXTRACTION RULE (new):
>
> Step 1: Scan elevations and detail sheets for labeled trim profiles.
>
> If a trim schedule exists (e.g. \'CASING TYPE A = 3-1/4\" bullnose
> MDF\'):
>
> Use the specified profile for all matching openings.
>
> Step 2: If no trim schedule exists, use these standard defaults:
>
> DOOR CASING (both sides of each door opening):
>
> CasingLF = 2 sides x \[(DoorHeight x 2 jambs) + (DoorWidth header)\]
>
> 6/8 door standard: approx 22 LF per door (both sides)
>
> 8/0 door (9ft wall): approx 24 LF per door (both sides)
>
> WINDOW CASING (interior side only):
>
> CasingLF = (2 x height) + (2 x width) + 6\" returns per window
>
> 3050 window: \~14 LF. 5050 window: \~20 LF. Rule: perimeter + 0.5\'
>
> BASE MOLDING:
>
> BaseLF = room perimeter - door opening widths
>
> Compute per room from floor plan, sum all rooms per floor.
>
> Step 3: Convert to purchase sticks:
>
> Casing -\> 7-ft and 16-ft sticks (MDF or finger-joint).
>
> Base -\> 16-ft sticks standard.
>
> Sticks = ceil(TotalLF / StickLength)
>
> Step 4: Output:
>
> MDF Casing 3-1/4\" bullnose (doors/windows): \[LF\] -\> \[N\] x 7-ft +
> \[N\] x 16-ft
>
> MDF Base 5\" bullnose: \[LF\] -\> \[N\] x 16-ft
>
> Note: Profile spec = owner/architect selection.
>
> No waste factor applied \-- GC to add cutting allowance.

**Quick Estimate for Burt Residence**

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Trim Type**               **Estimated LF** **Purchase (16-ft sticks)**
  --------------------------- ---------------- ---------------------------
  Door casing --- 31 interior 682 LF           43 EA 16-ft
  doors x 22 LF                                

  Door casing --- 9 exterior  216 LF           14 EA 16-ft
  doors x 24 LF                                

  Window casing --- 43        645 LF           41 EA 16-ft
  windows avg 15 LF                            

  Base molding --- 4,137 SF   \~690 LF         44 EA 16-ft
  floor area estimate                          

  Hook strip / crown (if      \~130 LF         9 EA 16-ft
  called)                                      

